[2]
Date: Mon 4 Jan 2010
Source: NRC Daily [Trans. and abridged Mod.AS, edited]
<http://www.nrc.nl/binnenland/article2448124.ece/Coutinho_alarmsysteem_voor_dierinfectieziekten>


Coutinho: alarm system for animal diseases
------------------------------------------
An alert system should be established, to detect dangerous infectious
diseases in cattle and other animals. This was said by infectious
disease fighter Roel Coutinho in an interview in this newspaper.

Due to the absence of such an alarm system, said Coutinho, new
infectious diseases remain invisible. Such diseases occur on farms
and threaten man as well. One example is the Q-fever, of which 6
people died this year.

Coutinho, Director of the Centre for Infectious Disease Control of
the RIVM [National Dutch Institute for Public Health and the
Environment], says this situation drives him to feel "powerless." "I
think there should be much more openness about what exactly happens
in the livestock industry." Due to the belated intervention in the Q
fever outbreak, 40 000 pregnant, including healthy, goats are
currently to be killed.

In the Netherlands, the risk that an animal disease will jump to
humans is considerable. There are many animals (119 million), the
contact between animals and humans is intense and the population
density is high.

The Ministry of Agriculture responded, saying that they have all
animal diseases "good in sight." A spokesman wonders "whether
Coutinho is indeed aware of the current state of affairs." The
ministry does not envisage a need for a change or improvement of the
existing systems.

[Byline: Hans van der Lugt and Hester van Santen]

